{"key":"post-10920156","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10920156</id>\n<content>Actually, until the last dozen or so years ago, cotton was the filter of choice for grain jars, autoclave bags, and liquid culture vials.&amp;nbsp; It must be kept dry of course, but dry cotton will filter as well as polyfill.&amp;nbsp; As said above, it's organic so if it gets wet, contaminants will attack it, but if kept dry it works fine.&amp;nbsp; It was the only filter material we had when I got started, right up until PFTE filter disks came out in the mid-eighties.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10920422</next>\n<prev>10919959</prev>\n<first>10919541</first>\n<last>10923291</last>\n<when>1251058790</when>\n<utime>08/23/09 11:19 PM</utime>\n</post>"}